{{- define "review-instructions" -}}
{{- if eq .Role "code-reviewer"}}

REVIEW SCOPE:
Evaluate: matches task def, matches spec, tests validate behavior, obvious defects, commit SHA.
Do NOT evaluate: style preferences, alternative approaches (unless defective), scope expansion.
Do NOT investigate: build system internals, packaging backends, or CI tooling. Flag build concerns as findings — don't probe them.
Review full worktree (base_commit → review_commit), not just latest changes.
Spec currency: validate against current spec version, not version at task creation.
Approval = meets requirements + spec + tests + no defects. Not: perfect or production-ready.

INSTRUCTIONS:
1. Early drift check: git -C {{.Worktree}} rev-parse HEAD — if it doesn't match REVIEW_COMMIT ({{.ReviewCommit}}), stop early (verdict submission will reject the mismatch).
2. Run tests: cd {{.Worktree}} && <project test command> (always cd first — never pass worktree paths as test runner arguments)
   If tests fail, TRIAGE ONLY — do not debug:
   git -C {{.Worktree}} diff --name-only {{.BaseCommit}}..{{.ReviewCommit}}
   Check: does any changed file share a package with the failing test?
   - No → pre-existing failure, note but do not reject for it
   - Yes → potential regression. Compare with base: git -C {{.Worktree}} show {{.BaseCommit}}:<path>
     If the change plausibly caused the failure → REJECT with the test name and failure output
     If unclear after reading the diff and base version → REJECT citing the test failure. Do not investigate further.
3. Review ALL changes: git -C {{.Worktree}} diff {{.BaseCommit}}..{{.ReviewCommit}}
   Each review is a fresh evaluation: "does this worktree satisfy the task?"
4. Invoke skill: code-review, then apply it to the full diff
5. If change touches specs/, introduces new abstractions, adds state/lifecycle, or spans 3+ modules: also invoke skill: systemic-thinking
6. TDD QUALITY (code tasks): Tests must cover done_when criteria — REJECT if tests are superficial or don't exercise the actual requirements
   Exception: mechanical test updates (file-path strings, import paths) caused by
   structural refactoring are NOT behavioral test changes — do not reject for these.
7. Test discovery (e.g. pytest, python -m unittest discover) finding 0 tests is a blocker — tests must be discoverable, not just runnable when explicitly named
8. Verify the done_when criteria are met AND tests exercise those criteria (for code tasks)
